This is an initial proposal for a new Terraform concept called "actions".

_Actions_ are a representation of a (possibly-non-idempotent) action that can be taken against a provider.
Examples include CDN cache invalidations, running arbitrary commands over SSH and running jobs in Rundeck.

Terraform's existing _provisioner_ concept already provides a way to model certain actions, but it is limited in the following ways:
- Provisioner actions can only be taken in response to the creation of a resource.
- Provisioners do not belong to providers (see #2756) and so it's difficult to provide a good UX for actions that call into remote service APIs.
- Provisioners cannot export results that can be used elsewhere in the configuration.  (see #610)

The first of these has been partially addressed via a design pattern around the `null_resource` resource, thus allowing provisioner actions to be run in response to certain updates too:

``` hcl
resource "null_resource" "example" {
    # Resource is re-created each time a trigger value changes...
    triggers = {
        ami_id = "${aws_instance.example.ami}"
    }

    # ...and then the provisioners get re-run
    provisioner "remote-exec" {
        # ...
    }
}
```

This proposal aims to "pave the cowpath" by building a first-class feature around this pattern while also attempting to address the other limitations.

Some use-cases:
- Invalidating a cache each time a resource is created _or_ updated
- Registering a server with Chef before it's created and then un-registering it once it's destroyed (See #649)
- Running arbitrary deployment actions with Rundeck, using the Rundeck provider
